### 3.  Related Work

##### Multi-modal Learning For Image Labelling

Despite the many recent successes of supervised neural networks

- It remains challenging to scale such models to large categories.
    - Solution: leverage additional information from other modalities
- Second, many work has focused on learning one-to-one mappings.
    - Solution: using a conditional probabilistic generative model

### 4. Conditional Adversarial Nets

#####  Generative Adversarial Nets

$$
\min_G \max_D V(G,D)=E_{x\sim p_{data}(x)}[\log D(x)]+E_{z\sim p_z(z)}[\log(1-D(G(z)))]
$$

#####  Conditional Adversarial Nets

GANs can be conditional if both $G$ and $D$ are conditioned on some extra info $y$. 

By feeding $y$ into the **both D  and D as additional input layer** (by concate)

- In $G$, prior input noise $p_z(z)$, and $y$ are concated in joint hidden reprsntatn
- In $D$, $x$ and $y$ are presented as inputs and to discriminative function.

The objective function of a two-player minimax game would be as :
$$
\min_G \max_D V(G,D)=E_{x\sim p_{data}(x)}[\log D(x|y)]+E_{z\sim p_z(z)}[\log(1-D(G(z|y)))]
$$

### 5. Experimental Results

##### Unimodal

Trained CGAN on MNIST conditioned on their labels, encoded as one-hot vec.

- In $G$, Both $z$ and $y$ are mapped to hidden layers and concatenated.
- The $D$ maps $x$ and $y$ to maxout layer respctvly before fed to sigmd layr.

##### Multimodal

Using CGANs to generate tag-vectors on image features for img auto-tagging.

- Image representation: train a CNN on ImgNet and using the last FC output
- World representation: using YFC mata, processing and ending up with a dict.

**In G**, noise and img feature contacted as input and mapped it to 200d reprsntatn.

**In D**, there are 500d word vec and 1200d img vec and maxout layer as the join layer which is finally fed to sigmoid layer.
